tes and the world economy can be accomplished only with major reforms on the scale of the New Deal and the post–World War II building of new global institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCapitalismzUnited States. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aamerican capitalism.  abusiness.  acapital.  acapitalism.  acapitalist economy.  acapitalist system.  achange the system.  aeconomic determinism.  aeconomic development.  aeconomic policy.  aeconomic sociology.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  afree enterprise.  aglobal institutions.  agovernmental action.  agovernments and governing.  amajor reforms.  amoney.  apolicy tools.  apolitical elites.  apolitical theory.  apolitics.  aprivate profit.  aprofit.  asociology.  athe new deal.  aunited states of america.  awealth and poverty.  awealth.  aworld economy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052028322040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520959071?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959071/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY